  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cpb-cou1-not-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-review-board",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Not accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team has determined that the CFD hemolysis prediction model for the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump does not meet the acceptance threshold for the stated COU under HIGH decision consequence, despite all assessed factors technically achieving their required Gradation levels at MRL 2. The rejection is based on the following structured reasoning: (1) Discretization error achieves Gradation 2 with a GCI of 2.7%, which satisfies the 5% threshold but provides limited margin. Given that the COU involves identifying worst-case hemolysis across tolerance variants that were not all directly meshed, the assessment team judges that the discretization evidence base is insufficient to support confident extrapolation to untested geometric configurations. (2) Model form achieves Gradation 2, but the 14.2% divergence between the power-law and mechanistic hemolysis models at operating point OP-2 (high-flow, low-speed) is a substantive concern. OP-2 corresponds to a clinically relevant off-design condition encountered during CPB weaning. The power-law model's known sensitivity to the empirical exponent in this flow regime means that worst-case identification at OP-2 carries elevated structural model uncertainty that is not fully resolved by the Gradation 2 evidence. (3) Taken together, the marginal discretization evidence and the model form divergence at a clinically significant operating point create a cumulative credibility gap that the assessment team judges to be inconsistent with the HIGH decision consequence of this COU. The decision consequence of HIGH — where an incorrect worst-case identification could lead to a device with clinically significant hemolysis levels reaching patients — requires a higher degree of confidence than the current evidence base provides. The team recommends: (a) conducting a fine-mesh (9.4M cell) simulation for the three most extreme tolerance variants to reduce discretization uncertainty; and (b) performing a targeted model form sensitivity study at OP-2 using the Arora mechanistic model to resolve the 14.2% divergence before resubmission. No procedural deficiencies were identified; the package is structurally complete and all evidence is appropriately documented.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
